questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot microservice randomly throws `NullPointerException` inside a read-only transactional service. The configurations are loaded lazily using a double-checked locking pattern as shown below:

java
@Service
public class ConfigurationService {
    private ConfigData configData;

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public ConfigData getConfig() {
        if (configData == null) {
            synchronized (this) {
                if (configData == null) {
                    configData = new ConfigData('PROD_DB', fetchSecrets());
                }
            } 
        }
        return configData;
    }
}

Heap dumps show that `configData` is indeed non-null when the failure occurs, yet some threads still read uninitialized or null fields within the `ConfigData` object.
